Alan Hevesi was the nominee of the Democratic Party for Comptroller. He served as Comptroller of New York City from 1994 to 2001 when he attempted a run for . Failing that, Hevesi ran for state Comptroller in 2002 defeating Republican challenger . In , controversial allegations regarding Hevesi's tenure as Comptroller arose including admitted use of a state employee as a chauffeur for his wife and the purported use of state employees along the campaign trail.[http://blogs.timesunion.com/capitol/?p=2226] [http://www.nydailynews.com/news/regional/story/456703p-384339c.html] At a commencement address he delivered at Queens College on June 1, 2006, Hevesi told his audience that Senator  was so tough he would "put a bullet between the president's eyes if he could get away with it." Several hours after his remarks, Hevesi apologized for his comments, calling them "beyond dumb," "remarkably stupid" and "incredibly moronic." [http://www.1010wins.com/pages/41908.php]
On , ,   ' office acknowledged that it is officially investigating actions by Hevesi regarding the public employee hired to chauffeur his wife. If Hevesi is found to have violated state ethics laws, he could be fined or possibly removed from office. [http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/newyork/ny-bc-ny--comptrollersrace1012oct12,0,19756.story?coll=ny-region-apnewyork] On , , Hevesi yielded control over his office to longtime political consultant . Rumors claim this is due to the investigation into his office over the scandal regarding his wife's chauffeur. [http://www.nypost.com/seven/10162006/news/columnists/hevesi_yields_power_columnists_fredric_u__dicker.htm]
On ,  the New York State Ethics Commission deemed that Hevesi's actions involving the chauffeur violated state law. It is currently in the hands of the New York State Assembly to determine the punishment for the crime. The found the following [http://blogs.nydailynews.com/dailypolitics/archives/2006/10/hevesi_in_troub.php]--
On , , Democratic  candidate  withdrew his endorsement of Hevesi saying, "Recent developments in the Comptroller’s race are deeply troubling. The outcome of the Ethics Commission investigation presents information that compromises Alan Hevesi's ability to fulfill his responsibilities." [http://blogs.nydailynews.com/dailypolitics/archives/2006/10/spitzers_statem.php]
On , , Hevesi was ordered to pay an additional $90,000. "Considering the record as a whole, I believe there is a preponderance of evidence that the comptroller knowingly and intentionally violated New York's public officers law," Kelley said in his 24-page report to Pataki. [http://www.abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory?id=2628830]
J. Christopher Callaghan was the nominee of the Republican Party for Comptroller. Callaghan was Treasurer for  from 1997 to early 2006 when he resigned to begin his campaign for state comptroller. There were reports that state party leaders were trying to recruit  Executive  to run for comptroller against Treasurer Callaghan. Vanderhoef announced that he was not running for comptroller and instead announced his candidacy for lieutenant governor. Callaghan spent much of the summer travelling to the many s throughout New York.
On , , Alan Hevesi admitted that he hired an employee of the state to drive around his wife after Callaghan made a public statement on the matter and called the "Comptroller's hotline." [http://www.callaghanfornewyork.com/press.php?op=job&jobid=137] Callaghan used the Comptroller's hotline during the campaign to call in misues of government funds specifically found in Hevesi's office.
